answers.body_markdown:
Not for a *stream* of data, no.  Streams are only one direction, and can&#39;t be replayed unless they&#39;re stored somewhere in memory or on disk for future replaying.

Think of a live TV event, or a radio playing.  You can&#39;t go back to see a thing happen in TV or rewind the radio unless you had something specific in memory to keep track of what was played.

The only way around this is to store the contents of the file itself so that you can recall them at some point.  Note that this can be *expensive* to do depending on how big the file is, which is why a lot of conventions recommend using streams to read the data instead.

Since you&#39;re reading a file, using [`Files.readAllLines()`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/nio/file/Files.html#readAllLines-java.nio.file.Path-) would be better.

```
Path filePath = Paths.get(&quot;C:\\Users\\Can\\Desktop\\girdiQuiz1.txt&quot;)
List&lt;String&gt; fileContents = Files.readAllLines(filePath);
```

From there, you can read individual lines out based on their index position in the list.

```
if(fileContents.get(0).equals(&quot;Default&quot;)) {
    // business logic
}
```

If you didn&#39;t precisely know what line it was, you could maintain a counter instead and re-called lines as necessary.

```
int line = 0;
for(String line : fileContents) {
    line++
    // do stuff with line
}
```

More curiously, with a `List` you *can* get access to [`List#listIterator`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/List.html#listIterator()) which will allow you to go backwards and forwards in the list as necessary.  Just...be careful about how you iterate over it.

