I use the standard practice of injecting my `ResourceBundle` into my JavaFX controllers using `FXMLLoader`:
```
class EditorController {

@FXML
private ResourceBundle resources;
 ...
}

```
And I specify my resource in the `FXMLLoader` constructor:
```
ResourceBundle resources = Resources.MESSAGES;
URL location = getClass().getResource(&quot;editor.fxml&quot;);

var loader = new FXMLLoader(location, resources);

class Resources {
    public static final MESSAGES = ResourceBundle.getBundle(&quot;messages&quot;);
}
```

I then use my injected `resource` instance in my controllers and supply it to any services that require it.

However, this is not directly possible when I have a custom JavaFX control inheriting from an existing control. For instance, consider the following `ReplaceDialog`:
```
